        <h2>Drawing management for different project types</h2>

        <h3>Residential remodeling and new construction</h3>
        <p>Drawing sets are typically smaller and simpler — architectural and structural plans, sometimes MEP. Buildertrend or Houzz Pro covers the basics. If you have a field team that does extensive drawing markup or punch list work, adding Fieldwire as a field layer is worth evaluating.</p>

        <h3>Commercial construction</h3>
        <p>Large, multi-discipline drawing sets with frequent revisions require robust version control and field access. Procore or Autodesk Build handles this at the enterprise level. Fieldwire works well as a field-specific drawing tool for superintendents who don't need the full PM platform.</p>

        <h3>Design-build projects</h3>
        <p>Projects where your team is involved in both design and construction benefit most from BIM-connected drawing management (Autodesk Build). The ability to connect field questions and issues back to the design model speeds up RFI resolution and reduces coordination errors.</p>

        <h2>Common drawing management mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Not superseding old revisions:</strong> Uploading Rev B without marking Rev A as outdated. Field teams work from the wrong set.</li>
          <li><strong>No field access:</strong> Drawings stored on the project manager's computer, inaccessible to field teams. Supers work from memory or outdated prints.</li>
          <li><strong>Unsaved markups:</strong> Handwritten notes on paper prints that never make it into the digital record. Field intelligence is lost.</li>
          <li><strong>No drawing linkage to RFIs:</strong> RFIs reference "see architectural Sheet A3" without a direct link. The architect can't find the question, response is delayed.</li>
          <li><strong>Subcontractors excluded:</strong> GC has drawing management; subs work from paper prints handed out at kick-off. Subs never see revisions.</li>
        </ul>

